@trentonbutler4067 There was faulty wiring causing the machine to randomly shut off or glitch throughout my shift. I filed an incident report each time, but I didn’t think anything was actually being done. Turns out, every report was auto logged with Westbrook, our third party repair company. After a handful of those reports, it triggered them to come out for what was technically a “random” inspection though it was clearly prompted by my reports.
They showed up on a Monday, shut down the machine, and did a full inspection. They quickly found the wiring issue and red-tagged the machine, deeming it inoperable until it was completely overhauled. The plant manager waited until they left and then removed the red tag. Since I was on night shift and this all happened during the day, I had no idea any of it had happened and he of course didn’t say a word. I came in and ran the machine like everything was normal for the next few shifts. Four days later, on Friday, the accident happened.
During discovery for our lawsuits, Westbrook’s paperwork was submitted as evidence. It explicitly stated that operating the machine before repairs were made “would likely result in grave injury or even death.” The plant manager admitted to removing the red tag, claiming he didn’t believe the issue was as serious as Westbrook made it out to be. OSHA’s investigation confirmed everything, as well as the investigators hired by the company.

